[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Web and mobile apps require a similar set of features on the backend, including notification service, integration with social networks, and cloud storage.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Each of these services has its own API that must be individually incorporated into an app, a process that can be time-consuming and complicated for app developers.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers form a bridge between the frontend of an application and various cloud-based backends via a unified API and SDK.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Providing a consistent way to manage backend data means that developers do not need to redevelop their own backend for each of the services that their apps need to access, potentially saving both time and money.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers offer different set of features and backend tools.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers also come in different types, suiting developers of different needs.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Most BaaS providers host backend platforms on their cloud servers.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] They also manage the infrastructure, security, and scalability of the platforms.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Developers can access the backend services via a web interface or the provided APIs.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Some examples of cloud-based BaaS include Firebase (hosted on Google Cloud Platform), AWS Amplify (hosted on Amazon Web Services), and Microsoft Azure Mobile Apps (hosted on Microsoft Azure).
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Self-hosted BaaS allow developers to host backend on their own servers, providing more flexibility and potential to customization compared to cloud-based BaaS, which often is more difficult to migrate from.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] However, developers are also in charge of managing the infrastructure, security, and scalability of their servers.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Mobile backend as a service (MBaaS) is a type of BaaS specifically for applications deployed in mobile systems.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] While some references use MBaaS interchangeably for BaaS, BaaS can have a wider variety of support such as for web apps and desktop apps.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers generate revenue from their services in various ways, often using a freemium model.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Under this model, a client receives a certain number of free active users or API calls per month, and pays a fee for each user or call over this limit.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Alternatively, clients can pay a set fee for a package which allows for a greater number of calls or active users per month.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] There are also flat fee plans that make the pricing more predictable.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Some of the providers offer the unlimited API calls inside their free plan offerings.
[src:firebase-firestore/backend-as-a-service] Another business model that has been used by a lot of BaaS providers is PAYG (pay as you go), which has a flexible cost based on developers' usage of database, storage, bandwidth, function calls, user numbers etc.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:firebase-firestore/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Its name continues as a set of backend cloud computing services and application development platforms provided by Google.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] It hosts databases, services, authentication, and integration for a variety of applications, including Android, iOS, JavaScript, Node.js, Java, Unity, PHP, and C++.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Firebase evolved from Envolve, a prior startup founded by James Tamplin and Andrew Lee in 2011.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Envolve provided developers an API that enables the integration of online chat functionality into their websites.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] After releasing the chat service, Tamplin and Lee found out that it was being used to pass application data that were not chat messages.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Developers were using Envolve to sync application data such as game state in real time across their users.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Tamplin and Lee decided to separate the chat system and the real-time architecture that powered it.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] They founded Firebase as a separate company in 2011 and it launched to the public in April 2012.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Firebase's first product was the Firebase Realtime Database, an API that synchronizes application data across iOS, Android, and Web devices, and stores it on Firebase's cloud.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] The product assists software developers in building real-time, collaborative applications.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] In May 2012, a month after the beta launch, Firebase raised $1.1 million in seed funding from venture capitalists Flybridge Capital Partners, Greylock Partners, Founder Collective, and New Enterprise Associates.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] In June 2013, the company further raised $5.6 million in Series A funding from Union Square Ventures and Flybridge Capital Partners.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] In 2014, Firebase launched two products: Firebase Hosting and Firebase Authentication.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] This positioned the company as a mobile backend as a service.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] In October 2014, Firebase was acquired by Google.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] A year later, in October 2015, Google acquired Divshot, an HTML5 web-hosting platform, to merge it with the Firebase team.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] In May 2016, at Google I/O, the company's annual developer conference, Google introduced Firebase Analytics and announced that it was expanding its services to become a unified backend-as-a-service (BaaS) platform for mobile developers.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Firebase now integrates with various other Google services, including Google Cloud Platform, AdMob, and Google Ads to offer broader products and scale for developers.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Google Cloud Messaging, the Google service to send push notifications to Android devices, was superseded by a Firebase product, Firebase Cloud Messaging, which added the functionality to deliver push notifications to Android, iOS and web devices.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] In July 2016 Google announced that it was acquiring the mobile developer platform LaunchKit, which specialized in app developer marketing, and would be folding it into the Firebase Growth Tools team.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] In January 2017, Google acquired Fabric and Crashlytics from Twitter to add those services to Firebase.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] In October 2017 Google launched Cloud Firestore, a real-time document database as the successor product to the original Firebase Realtime Database.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] Firebase software has been claimed to be used by Google to track users without their knowledge.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] On July 14, 2020, a lawsuit was filed accusing Google of violating federal wire tap law and California privacy law.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] It stated that through Firebase, Google collected and stored user data, logging what the user was looking at in many types of apps, despite the user following Google's own instructions to turn off the web and app activity collected by the company.
[src:firebase-firestore/firebase] The lawsuit was dismissed in January 2022, with Chief US District Judge Richard Seeborg ruling that a promise to avoid collecting user data did not amount to a contract.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Cloud Firestore is a NoSQL, document-oriented database.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Unlike a SQL database, there are no tables or rows.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Instead, you store data in *documents*, which are organized into *collections*.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Each *document* contains a set of key-value pairs.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Cloud Firestore is optimized for storing large collections of small documents.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] All documents must be stored in collections.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Documents can contain *subcollections* and nested objects, both of which can include primitive fields like strings or complex objects like lists.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Collections and documents are created implicitly in Cloud Firestore.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Simply assign data to a document within a collection.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] If either the collection or document does not exist, Cloud Firestore creates it.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] In Cloud Firestore, the unit of storage is the document.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] A document is a lightweight record that contains fields, which map to values.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Complex, nested objects in a document are called maps.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] You may notice that documents look a lot like JSON.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] There are some differences (for example, documents support extra data types and are limited to the document size limit), but in general, you can treat documents as lightweight JSON records.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Documents live in collections, which are simply containers for documents.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Cloud Firestore is schemaless, so you have complete freedom over what fields you put in each document and what data types you store in those fields.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] Documents within the same collection can all contain different fields or store different types of data in those fields.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] However, it's a good idea to use the same fields and data types across multiple documents, so that you can query the documents more easily.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] A collection contains documents and nothing else.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] It can't directly contain raw fields with values, and it can't contain other collections.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] The names of documents within a collection are unique.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] You can provide your own keys, such as user IDs, or you can let Cloud Firestore create random IDs for you automatically.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] You do not need to "create" or "delete" collections.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] After you create the first document in a collection, the collection exists.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore-data-model] If you delete all of the documents in a collection, it no longer exists.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Save and categorize content based on your preferences.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Use our flexible, scalable NoSQL cloud database, built on Google Cloud infrastructure, to store and sync data for client- and server-side development.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Cloud Firestore is a flexible, scalable database for mobile, web, and server development from Firebase and Google Cloud.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Like Firebase Realtime Database, it keeps your data in sync across client apps through realtime listeners and offers offline support for mobile and web so you can build responsive apps that work regardless of network latency or Internet connectivity.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Cloud Firestore also offers seamless integration with other Firebase and Google Cloud products, including Cloud Run functions.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Cloud Firestore has two editions - Firestore Standard edition and Firestore Enterprise edition to meet different needs.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Here's where you can learn more about these editions.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Cloud Firestore is a cloud-hosted, NoSQL database that your Apple, Android, and web apps can access directly using native SDKs.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Cloud Firestore is also available in native Node.js, Java, Python, Unity, C++ and Go SDKs, in addition to REST and RPC APIs.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Following Cloud Firestore's document data model, you store data that contain fields mapping to values.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] These documents are stored in collections, which are containers for your documents that you can use to organize your data and build queries.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Documents support many different data types, from simple strings and numbers, to complex, nested objects.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] You can also create subcollections within documents and build hierarchical data structures that scale as your database grows.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] The Cloud Firestore data model supports whatever data structure works best for your app.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Additionally, querying in Cloud Firestore is expressive, efficient, and flexible.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Create shallow queries to retrieve data at the document level without needing to retrieve the entire collection, or any nested subcollections.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Add sorting, filtering, and limits to your queries or cursors to paginate your results.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] To keep data in your apps current, without retrieving your entire database each time an update happens, add real-time listeners.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Adding real-time listeners to your app notifies you with a data snapshot whenever the data your client apps are listening to changes, retrieving only the new changes.
[src:firebase-firestore/firestore] Protect access to your data in Cloud Firestore with Firebase Authentication and Cloud Firestore Security Rules for Android, Apple platforms, and JavaScript, or Identity and Access Management (IAM) for server-side languages.
